":"circa 1290","1290":"1290","of,Uwch Gwyrfai cmt,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1250–":"about 1250–Deceased","1246–Male":"1246–Deceased","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","about 1250":"about 1250","1246":"1246","1250":"1250","ABT    1290":"about 1290","1290":"1290","of,Uwch Gwyrfai cmt,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Llywelyn ap Maredudd Bengoch was born about 1250, in Montgomeryshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Llywelyn ap Maredudd Bengoch."},"et":{"about 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1246–Male":"1246–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1246":"1246","1250":"1250","ABT    1290":"umbes 1290","1290":"1290","of,Uwch Gwyrfai cmt,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1250–":"noin 1250–Kuollut","1246–Male":"1246–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","1246":"1246","1250":"1250","ABT    1290":"noin 1290","1290":"1290","of,Uwch Gwyrfai cmt,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1250–":"environ 1250–Décédée","1246–Male":"1246–Décédé","1290–Male":"1290–Décédé","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","about 1250":"environ 1250","1246":"1246","1250":"1250","ABT    1290":"environ 1290","1290":"1290","of,Uwch Gwyrfai cmt,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Llywelyn ap Maredudd Bengoch est née environ 1250, à Montgomeryshire, Galles. El